tory, the articles take a close look at women's status in ancient, medieval, modern, and contemporary Christianity. Contributors explore such themes as women's role in early Christian communities, their role models in the Roman Empire, Elizabeth I's exploitation of women's cultural disadvantages, the relative autonomy of women in Catholic and Protestant churches, and their evolving roles in marriage and the ministry today.This fascinating history of women's response to sexism in Christianity is an ideal text for courses in women's studies and church history. Lively, clear, and jargon-free, it will also appeal to anyone with a special interest in this wide-ranging subject.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSexismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aWomen in Christianity. 0aWomenxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Christian Life / General.2bisacsh1 aD\x27angelo, Mary Rose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher-Marsh, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHegy, Pierre, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHégy, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeonard, Ellen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarios, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, Molly T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartos, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartos, Joseph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMayeski, Marie Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPohlhaus, Gaile M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteinhauser, Kenneth B., econtri